2026-04-16 12:39:31 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module output connector / wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='All components inside the PSU and load modules measure nominal (battery, PSU LED/resistor, load protection diode, both lamps, and all cabling continuity). The relay coil and contacts in the control module are confirmed to close properly and present ~12 V on the relay output node. However, only ~0.36 V ever appears on the external output pair of the control module and at the load‑module input, even though continuity from relay contacts to both output cables tests as ‘nominal’ at low voltage/ohms.\n\nThis indicates that under operating conditions the 12 V from the relay output is being heavily loaded or partially shorted before or at the external output connector, clamping the voltage to ~0.36 V. Because the load module (when disconnected) tests normally and the protection diode is not shorted, the most consistent explanation is a fault at the control module’s output connector or immediately adjacent PCB/wiring: e.g., a partial short between the + output and −/ground, a damaged trace or solder bridge, or an internal misconnection that only shows up under applied voltage. This fault prevents the control module from delivering 12 V to the load while still reading as ‘continuous’ with a multimeter.\n\nTherefore the root cause is a faulty control (ambient sensor) module output connection/wiring that clamps the output voltage; repairing or replacing the control module’s output connector or the small section of wiring/PCB from the relay to that connector should restore normal lamp operation.'
