2026-04-16 12:40:51 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module internal protection diode orientation / polarity (installed reversed or wired backwards between + input and lamp node)'] hypothesis_explanation='All three modules and the interconnections show nominal continuity and component values. The PSU delivers 12 V and its LED works. The control module input sees 12 V, the relay coil and contacts operate correctly, and continuity from the relay output to the external output terminals is nominal. Yet, when the relay closes, only about 0.36 V appears at the control‑module output and at the load‑module input, even though open‑circuit tests show no short in the load: the lamps have their expected resistances (≈120 Ω and 500 Ω), the diode forward drop tests at ~0.7 V, and the load input wiring has ≈0.1 Ω resistance. This means the 12 V is being strongly loaded or clamped internally whenever the load module is connected, but that effect disappears in diode‑test/ohms mode.\n\nA plausible single‑point cause is that the series protection diode inside the load module is installed or wired in reverse with respect to the external polarity marking. In normal operation with correct polarity, the diode would be reverse‑biased, blocking most current and leaving only a small leakage current, so the control‑module output is dragged up slightly from 0 toward ~0.3–0.4 V (a typical reverse‑leakage or bias voltage in the resistor network) but never reaches 12 V. In multimeter diode mode, however, the meter drives only a small current and measures the junction in the forward direction at its terminals, so the diode reads as a normal 0.7 V junction. The lamps appear normal but never actually see forward current because the diode is oriented to block it in the powered configuration.\n\nNo previous repair attempts targeted the *orientation or wiring* of the protection diode; they only verified or replaced the diode as a component and the wiring to the lamps. Therefore the most likely remaining fault is that the protection diode is functionally reversed or connected to the wrong node inside the load module, preventing the 12 V from ever reaching the lamps while loading the control output to about 0.36 V.'
