2026-04-16 12:42:01 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module internal protection diode orientation / polarity (relative to external +/− labels and connector pinout)', 'load module external connector / cable mapping (load + and − leads mislabeled or cross‑wired relative to internal diode)'] hypothesis_explanation="All active components and obvious fault candidates have been ruled out, and the control module is confirmed to deliver ~12 V at its relay contacts with correct polarity referenced to the power supply. Yet only ~0.36 V appears at the control output and at the load input, even though continuity of all cables and the load’s protection diode and lamps test nominal. This indicates that under operating conditions the load module is effectively clamping the line to a small voltage rather than drawing normal current.\n\nGiven that the protection diode itself measures healthy (Vf≈0.7 V, no short) and that internal wiring from the diode to the lamps was previously found nominal, the remaining consistent explanation is a *systematic polarity mismatch between the load module’s external '+' / '−' identification and its internal diode orientation*. In other words, the diode is internally wired in the correct direction relative to the lamps, but the external connector or cable labeling is reversed or cross‑wired, so that when the modules are connected with the assumed polarity, the diode is reverse‑biased. The control module then drives into a reverse‑biased diode plus some leakage paths and measurement loading, resulting in a small residual voltage (~0.36 V) at the load input instead of 12 V; the lamps never see forward current and remain off.\n\nThis is not an intrinsic failure of the silicon diode itself (already tested), but a configuration/assembly error involving the diode’s orientation relative to the external connector pinout or the mapping of the load module’s external cables. Correcting the polarity mapping between the load module’s internal diode/lamp node and its external '+' and '−' leads should restore normal operation."
