2026-04-16 12:42:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module internal light‑sensor / threshold circuit causing unintended rapid toggling of relay (oscillatory behavior)'] hypothesis_explanation='All connectors, cable polarities, relay contacts, power‑supply voltage, load‑module diode and lamp paths have now been effectively ruled out by direct electrical tests or prior incorrect hypotheses. The PSU delivers a solid 12 V and its LED is stable. The load module and its protection diode measure nominal; when disconnected, they present normal resistances and no abnormal leakage that could clamp the line near 0.36 V. The control‑module output, however, only reaches ~0.36 V despite ~12 V at the input and verified continuity through the relay to the output terminals. This strongly indicates that some circuitry inside the control module, in parallel with or feeding the relay drive, is loading or intermittently toggling the supply rather than a simple wiring or relay fault.\n\nThe original symptom was a lamp that turned off every ~20 s for ~0.5 s, classic of an incorrectly behaving timing/threshold network in the ambient‑sensor subsystem (RC timing, hysteresis around the comparator, or the light‑sensor bias network). After the timing and sensitivity potentiometers were swept, the lamp no longer turns on at all, meaning the internal threshold/oscillator network has moved into a state where the relay is never held fully on or the output is heavily loaded. The measured ~0.36 V at the control‑module output when the relay is supposedly closed is consistent with an internal fault in the light‑sensor/threshold circuitry pulling the output node toward ground or otherwise preventing a solid 12 V from reaching the relay coil and contacts. \n\nGiven that relay contacts, wiring to the connector, indicator LED path, and supply path from the PSU into the control board have all been explicitly ruled out via prior failed repair attempts, the only remaining plausible root cause within the control module is a defect in the light‑sensor / comparator / threshold network (e.g., faulty comparator IC, misbiased transistor, or failed RC component) causing unintended oscillation and, after adjustment, permanent mis‑drive of the relay. Repairing or replacing this internal light‑sensor/threshold circuit should restore stable 12 V switching to the load and eliminate the intermittent lamp outages.'
