2026-04-16 12:42:50 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module internal series resistor in output path to indicator LED and load (incorrect high resistance value or wrong component fitted)'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show ~12 V present on the control‑module input and across the closed relay, but only ~0.36 V appears at the control‑module output and at the load‑module input, with correct polarity and with all cabling and relay contacts verified as having nominal low resistance. The load module lamps and protection diode also test nominal, and swapping/repairing connectors and diode orientation had no effect. This strongly implies that the supply is being dropped inside the control module by a deliberately placed series element after the relay, rather than by contact resistance or the load module. The only remaining plausible element in that path is a series resistor feeding the “switched‑cables indicator” LED / output node. If that resistor has an incorrect (very high) value or the wrong component was installed in that position, the output node would be clamped to a small fraction of 12 V (here ~0.36 V) under load, matching the observed behavior both initially (intermittent lamp operation as the control circuit drove the node) and after adjustments (lamp now never lights because the available voltage is far below the lamps’ thresholds). Therefore, the most likely fault is an incorrect or faulty high‑value series resistor in the control module’s output path feeding the indicator LED and load, effectively creating an unintended large series resistance between the relay output and the external output terminals.'
