2026-04-16 12:43:05 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['lamp in load module (main external bulb)', 'internal indicator lamp in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='The control module is confirmed to receive a proper 12 V from the power‑supply module and its relay closes with low resistance. Continuity from the relay output through the control‑module output connector and the cable to the load module is nominal, with no excessive series resistance or polarity inversion. The protection diode in the load module tests normal (about 0.7 V forward drop, good reverse blocking), and continuity from the load‑module input terminals through the diode path is low ohms. Despite this, when connected, the control‑module output is pulled down to about 0.36 V at both the control output and the load input, indicating that the load module is presenting an unexpectedly heavy load (very low effective resistance) that clamps the supply well below 12 V.\n\nAll external wiring, connectors, diode orientation, internal supply paths, series resistors, indicator circuits, and the power source itself have already been ruled out by previous (unsuccessful) repair attempts. The only remaining components inside the load module that could create such a strong loading effect are the main lamp and the internal indicator lamp. A partial short or internal fault in one or both lamps could still allow them to show a near‑normal resistance reading at low test voltages (ohmmeter), yet under actual 12 V operation they could behave as a much lower resistance or intermittent short, collapsing the voltage to ~0.36 V and preventing illumination.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is that the lamps themselves (main external bulb and/or internal indicator bulb) are faulty under operating conditions, effectively loading the supply and preventing normal 12 V from appearing at the load node, which explains both the original intermittent flicker and the current complete loss of illumination.'
