2026-04-16 12:43:40 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module internal light sensor element (photodiode/phototransistor)'] hypothesis_explanation='The system draws only ~1.7 mA from the battery when the relay is commanded on, while ~100 mA would be expected if the load were being driven with 12 V. The power‑supply voltage is correct at the control‑module input, the relay coil and contacts have been verified good, and continuity from the relay output to the external output cables and into the load input is nominal. All series components in the output path (indicator LED, resistors, load protection diode, lamps) measure with correct values and orientation, and multiple hypotheses about mis‑wiring or connector polarity have already been disproved by direct repair attempts.\n\nGiven that: (1) the relay closes but essentially no load current flows; (2) the control output and the load input sit at about 0.36 V instead of being pulled up to 12 V; and (3) there is no low‑resistance or leaky fault found in the load path, the most consistent explanation is that the control module never truly drives the relay coil solidly because its light‑sensor front end is faulty. A failed photodiode/phototransistor (e.g., internally leaky or with wrong characteristics) can bias the threshold/comparator network such that the driver never saturates, the relay armature only weakly engages (or chatters), and the circuit behaves as a nearly open high‑resistance path. This would produce a small current (~mA), a low residual voltage (~0.36 V) at the supposed 12 V output, and the observed intermittent flicker that vanished when the timing/sensitivity potentiometers were adjusted.\n\nTherefore, the most likely single faulty component remaining is the internal light‑sensor element in the control (ambient sensor) module. Replacing that sensor (or its small sub‑assembly) should restore normal operation.'
