description: With the control module opened, trace the PCB or internal wiring from the relay’s switched contact (the side that should feed the load) to the external output terminals. Using a multimeter, measure continuity from the relay output pad/lead to each of the two output terminals and verify which terminal (if any) is actually connected. Also check for any series components (indicator LED, resistor, or miswired trace) that could be dropping the voltage from ~12 V at the relay to ~0.36 V at the external output., outcome='Control relay contacts and both control output cables (+ and −) show nominal continuity.  \nPSU status LED, load protection diode, and associated resistors (PSU green LED resistor and sensor bias resistor) all measure at their nominal values.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=155.0, cost_breakdown=[('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_diode', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_diode', 20.0), ('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> load module input cables and internal wiring,
description: With the system assembled and the relay confirmed closed, measure the voltage directly at the load‑module input terminals (on the load box side of the connector). Then open the load module and measure continuity from each input terminal to the points just before and after the series protection diode, and to the lamp/indicator nodes. This will determine whether there is an unexpected drop or miswiring inside the load module that prevents the ~12 V from the control output from reaching the lamps., outcome='Voltage at the load input is very low (~0.36 V on Load Input Cable (+), ~0 V on Load Input Cable (−)) despite nominal continuity on both load input cables and both lamps. The load module inspection panel could not be opened, and the protection diode’s continuity could not be measured with the available method.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=145.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> load module protection diode / internal supply path,
description: Disconnect the load module from the control module. With the load module opened if possible, use a multimeter in diode/ohms mode to test the series protection diode (from the + input terminal to the lamp node): measure forward voltage and check for reverse blocking or a short. Also measure resistance from the + input terminal to the lamp node and from the − input terminal to the lamp return. This will reveal whether the diode is shorted, open, or if there is an unintended low‑resistance path inside the load module that is clamping the control‑module output to ~0.36 V., outcome='The inspection panel on the load module could not be opened, so internal access was not obtained. The load protection diode tests nominal with Vf = 0.700 V in diode mode, and both load input cables (+ and −) show nominal low resistance (0.10 Ω) continuity with no indicated faults. The main load lamp (120 Ω) and internal indicator lamp (500 Ω) both measure nominal resistance.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=105.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_diode', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> complete assembled system – measure current from PSU into control+load chain,
description: Insert an ammeter (or a low‑value shunt with voltmeter) in series with the positive lead between the power‑supply module and the control module, with the relay commanded ON (lamp supposed to be lit). Measure the total current drawn from the battery. Compare it with the expected load current (~12 V / 120 Ω ≈ 100 mA plus indicator). This will reveal whether the control+load chain is actually drawing near‑normal lamp current (implying most of the 12 V is being dropped somewhere in series) or only a few mA (implying a high‑resistance or unintended series element between PSU and load)., outcome='The requested action could not be mapped to any recognized diagnostic operation. Only actions from the available action list are supported (e.g. measure_voltage, test_continuity, inspect_connections, verify_repair, …).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=0.0, cost_breakdown=[], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> complete assembled system – series current from PSU to control+load chain,
description: Insert an ammeter (or a known low‑value shunt with voltmeter) in series with the positive lead between the power‑supply module and the control module, with the relay definitely commanded ON (lamp supposed to be lit). Measure the total current drawn from the battery and report the reading. This will distinguish between a normal ~100 mA lamp current (implying most of the 12 V is dropped across an unintended series impedance) and a very small current (implying a high‑resistance/open path that clamps the control output around 0.36 V)., outcome='Measured current through PSU Output Cable (+) is 0.001666 A (1.666 mA).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=20.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_current', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
